PGP verification trusts a release-bundled public key
Link: https://chatgpt.com/codex/cloud/security/findings/59f9a5b30a288191a71a017014713bc5?sev=critical%2Chigh
Criticality: high (attack path: high)
Status: new

# Metadata
Repo: hatolife/ClipForVRChat
Commit: 749bd2e
Author: poppo@hato.life
Created: 2026/6/29 13:21:12
Assignee: Unassigned
Signals: Security, Validated, Patch generated, Attack-path

# Summary
Introduced a release-integrity verification flaw in the new PGP signing guidance and release asset publication. The signing operation itself creates a valid detached signature, but the public key distribution and user instructions make the verification susceptible to key substitution.
The new release workflow exports `ClipForVRChat-release-signing-public-key.asc` as another release asset, and both README/UI guidance instruct users to import that key from the same release before verifying `ClipForVRChat.exe.asc`. The UI further states that seeing `Good signature` means the executable is confirmed as official. This lacks a trust anchor: users are not given an out-of-band fingerprint, embedded/pinned public key, or other independent way to confirm that the imported key is the project's real release key. Therefore, compromise of the release assets, a malicious mirror, or any substituted download bundle can bypass the intended signature check by replacing the exe, asc, and public key together.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Confirm the commit publishes the detached signature and public key as release assets alongside the executable/zip.
- [x] Confirm README/UI instructions tell users to import the public key from the same release before verification.
- [x] Confirm there is no independent trust anchor such as a pinned fingerprint or embedded public key in user-facing guidance.
- [x] Demonstrate that a substituted executable, signature, and public key produce GPG exit code 0 and `Good signature` in a clean verifier keyring.
- [x] Check whether the guidance overstates `Good signature` as proof of official origin despite GPG reporting the imported key as uncertified/unknown.
## Report
Validated the suspected release-integrity flaw. The commit adds a signing step in `.github/workflows/release.yml:85-107` that creates `ClipForVRChat.exe.asc`, verifies it locally, then exports the signing public key to `dist/ClipForVRChat-release-signing-public-key.asc`. The release publication block at `.github/workflows/release.yml:109-116` publishes the zip, `.sha256`, `.asc`, and exported public key together as mutable release assets. User guidance then tells users to import that public key from the same release: `README.md:29-31` says to download `ClipForVRChat.exe.asc` and import `ClipForVRChat-release-signing-public-key.asc` from the same release before verifying. The in-app guidance at `src/frontend/src/main.js:671-674` similarly instructs users to use the same-release `.asc` and same-release public key, run `gpg --verify`, and treats `Good signature` as confirmation that the exe is official. A targeted grep for fingerprint/key anchors found no user-facing pinned fingerprint or embedded public key in README/UI; the only fingerprint-related user-facing line is `issues/038-about-official-distribution-and-pgp.md:20`, which explicitly says not to show the release-signing public-key fingerprint in the information screen. I reproduced the trust-substitution problem with a minimal GPG PoC: generated an attacker key, created a fake `ClipForVRChat.exe`, signed it, exported the attacker's public key under the expected release asset name, imported that same-release key into a fresh verifier keyring, and ran the documented verification command. GPG exited 0 and printed `Good signature from "ClipForVRChat Release Signing Key (attacker-supplied) <attacker@example.invalid>" [unknown]`, proving that if exe/signature/key are substituted together, the documented `Good signature` check succeeds without any independent trust anchor. Crash/valgrind/debugger attempts were considered because the repo contains Go code, but this vulnerability is a release process/documentation integrity flaw rather than a memory-safety flaw. A crash-oriented execution of the PoC returned exit 0 as expected; `valgrind` was unavailable; running the same GPG verification under `lldb` showed the process printed `Good signature` and exited status 0.

